16
00:00:52,619 --> 00:00:56,121
   the french game of pétanque  
       is somewhat similar      

17
00:00:56,123 --> 00:00:58,157
  to the italian game of bocce  

18
00:00:58,159 --> 00:01:00,626
      and the british game      
        of lawn bowling.        

19
00:01:00,628 --> 00:01:02,595
        it's played with        
       hollow steel balls       

20
00:01:02,597 --> 00:01:06,432
          called boules         
  on a dirt or gravel surface.  

21
00:01:06,434 --> 00:01:08,900
     the object of the game     
      is to toss the balls      

22
00:01:08,902 --> 00:01:13,705
      as close as possible      
     to a small wooden ball.    

23
00:01:13,707 --> 00:01:17,309
   the first pétanque players   
  carved their balls from wood. 

24
00:01:17,311 --> 00:01:20,713
       by the late 1800s,       
    players hammered in nails   

25
00:01:20,715 --> 00:01:22,414
   to make their balls heftier  

26
00:01:22,416 --> 00:01:25,584
    and less likely to crack    
    when hitting other balls.   

27
00:01:25,586 --> 00:01:27,119
      then came brass balls     

28
00:01:27,121 --> 00:01:29,888
      and later the hollow      
     steel balls used today.    

29
00:01:29,890 --> 00:01:31,524
                     ♪♪         

30
00:01:31,526 --> 00:01:34,626
      manufacturing begins      
    with long bars of carbon    

31
00:01:34,628 --> 00:01:36,028
       or stainless steel,      

32
00:01:36,030 --> 00:01:38,697
 about 1 1/2 inches in diameter.

33
00:01:38,699 --> 00:01:40,298
    this is stainless steel.    

34
00:01:40,300 --> 00:01:45,203
  an automated saw cuts pieces  
     about 1 3/4 inch long.     

35
00:01:45,205 --> 00:01:47,573
    workers place the pieces    
         on a conveyer,         

36
00:01:47,575 --> 00:01:50,376
        which moves them        
     into an induction oven.    

37
00:01:50,378 --> 00:01:53,712
       the oven heats them      
        to between 1,650        

38
00:01:53,714 --> 00:01:56,448
  and 2,190 degrees fahrenheit, 

39
00:01:56,450 --> 00:01:58,918
      softening the steel.      

40
00:01:58,920 --> 00:02:01,252
       as soon as a piece       
     comes out of the oven,     

41
00:02:01,254 --> 00:02:04,356
        the forging press       
     strikes it three times,    

42
00:02:04,358 --> 00:02:07,826
first flattening it into a disk.

43
00:02:07,828 --> 00:02:10,763
    next, thinning the disk,    

44
00:02:10,765 --> 00:02:13,699
     then stamping the disk     
       into a half sphere.      

45
00:02:13,701 --> 00:02:19,471
                     ♪♪         

46
00:02:19,473 --> 00:02:21,640
     workers mill the forged    
           half sphere          

47
00:02:21,642 --> 00:02:23,842
 on a lathe to refine the shape 

48
00:02:23,844 --> 00:02:27,345
 and to create a gap they later 
      fill with metal wire      

49
00:02:27,347 --> 00:02:31,916
   when they weld this half to  
 another half to form the ball. 

50
00:02:31,918 --> 00:02:35,921
a worker drops the milled halves
    down two separate chutes    

51
00:02:35,923 --> 00:02:40,825
and deliver two halves at a time
to an automated welding machine.

52
00:02:40,827 --> 00:02:42,995
       the machine clamps       
       the halves together      

53
00:02:42,997 --> 00:02:45,630
  and welds them to each other. 

54
00:02:45,632 --> 00:02:48,800
    a robot removes the ball    
    from the welding machine    

55
00:02:48,802 --> 00:02:52,471
      and transfers it to a     
computer-guided milling machine.

56
00:02:52,473 --> 00:02:56,508
  as the machine's lathe spins  
  the ball, a knife shaves off  

57
00:02:56,510 --> 00:02:59,244
      thin layers of steel      
       to smooth the ball       

58
00:02:59,246 --> 00:03:01,479
  and make the weld invisible.  

59
00:03:01,481 --> 00:03:04,416
     this also puts the ball    
   within a specific diameter   

60
00:03:04,418 --> 00:03:07,719
 and weight range in accordance 
    with international rules    

61
00:03:07,721 --> 00:03:10,422
      governing the sport.      

62
00:03:10,424 --> 00:03:13,658
    the machine also engraves   
   a pattern to help identify   

63
00:03:13,660 --> 00:03:15,460
     whose balls are whose.     

64
00:03:15,462 --> 00:03:20,498
                     ♪♪         

65
00:03:20,500 --> 00:03:22,901
  international pétanque rules  
         require a ball         

66
00:03:22,903 --> 00:03:25,771
       to have four items       
  engraved into its surface --  

67
00:03:25,773 --> 00:03:28,140
         the brand name,        
        the pattern name,       

68
00:03:28,142 --> 00:03:30,608
     the weight of the ball,    
       and a serial number      

69
00:03:30,610 --> 00:03:34,045
      for the set to which      
           it belongs.          

70
00:03:34,047 --> 00:03:37,049
     once the brand, pattern    
    and weight are engraved,    

71
00:03:37,051 --> 00:03:41,420
 the balls move along a conveyor
  toward the tempering station. 

72
00:03:41,422 --> 00:03:43,221
   cutting, heating, forging,   

73
00:03:43,223 --> 00:03:46,324
       and machining steel      
   makes it brittle and weak.   

74
00:03:46,326 --> 00:03:48,627
    tempering is the process    
         of hardening it        

75
00:03:48,629 --> 00:03:50,495
    to restore its strength.    

76
00:03:50,497 --> 00:03:54,365
     after heating the ball     
        to between 1,470        

77
00:03:54,367 --> 00:03:57,603
  and 1,830 degrees fahrenheit, 

78
00:03:57,605 --> 00:04:01,507
   they immediately cool it in  
 water that's about 104 degrees,

79
00:04:01,509 --> 00:04:03,976
  a process known as quenching. 

80
00:04:03,978 --> 00:04:07,513
   after tempering the steel,   
  manufacturers polish the ball 

81
00:04:07,515 --> 00:04:09,881
    with an automated sander.   

82
00:04:09,883 --> 00:04:12,351
       the finished balls       
        do vary slightly,       

83
00:04:12,353 --> 00:04:15,954
 so this last automated machine 
         weighs each one        

84
00:04:15,956 --> 00:04:18,356
      and sorts it in rows      
      of identical weight.      

85
00:04:18,358 --> 00:04:20,992
                     ♪♪         

86
00:04:20,994 --> 00:04:24,329
    then, equal weight balls    
  are grouped in sets of three  

87
00:04:24,331 --> 00:04:28,533
      and are engraved with     
     the same serial number.    

88
00:04:28,535 --> 00:04:31,870
      these pétanque balls      
    are made of carbon steel.   

89
00:04:31,872 --> 00:04:34,073
      to prevent oxidation      
         and corrosion,         

90
00:04:34,075 --> 00:04:37,009
    the factory electroplates   
     its carbon steel balls     

91
00:04:37,011 --> 00:04:39,945
        with a protective       
       layer of chromium.       

92
00:04:39,947 --> 00:04:43,215
     it submerges the balls     
  in a series of chemical baths 

93
00:04:43,217 --> 00:04:45,917
         and water baths        
       to prep the surface      

94
00:04:45,919 --> 00:04:49,021
        for the final dip       
    in an electroplating tank   

95
00:04:49,023 --> 00:04:51,823
 in which an electrical current 
    draws chromium particles    

96
00:04:51,825 --> 00:04:56,795
 through the water and deposits 
  them onto the ball's surface. 

97
00:04:56,797 --> 00:05:00,566
     the chromium treatment     
      leaves a white film.      

98
00:05:00,568 --> 00:05:06,772
this brushing machine removes it
 and restores the shiny finish. 

99
00:05:06,774 --> 00:05:10,475
   international rules require  
   pétanque balls to be 2 3/4   

100
00:05:10,477 --> 00:05:13,212
          to just over          
      3 inches in diameter      

101
00:05:13,214 --> 00:05:17,582
     and weigh between 1 1/2    
        to 1 3/4 pounds.        

102
00:05:17,584 --> 00:05:20,885
     the retail box contains    
      three identical balls     

103
00:05:20,887 --> 00:05:23,254
     engraved with the same     
         serial number,         

104
00:05:23,256 --> 00:05:25,190
           along with           
      the wood target ball,     

105
00:05:25,192 --> 00:05:29,661
        a cleaning cloth,       
      and a warranty card.      

106
00:05:29,663 --> 00:05:32,264
      the goal of the game      
  is to toss the balls as close 

107
00:05:32,266 --> 00:05:34,666
 as possible to the target ball 

108
00:05:34,668 --> 00:05:37,636
  while knocking the opponents' 
       balls away from it.      

109
00:05:37,638 --> 00:05:40,005
   and the player's feet must   
      remain planted inside     

110
00:05:40,007 --> 00:05:41,874
  a small circle when tossing.  

111
00:05:44,678 --> 00:05:47,245
  you can play pétanque indoors 
           in a venue           

112
00:05:47,247 --> 00:05:50,048
      known as a boulodrome     
          or boule bar,         

113
00:05:50,050 --> 00:05:51,717
    or you can play outdoors    

114
00:05:51,719 --> 00:05:55,320
    anywhere there's a patch    
   of relatively flat ground.   

115
00:06:05,899 --> 00:06:10,535
                     ♪♪         

116
00:06:10,537 --> 00:06:12,971
  narrator: biologic medicines  
          are proteins          

117
00:06:12,973 --> 00:06:15,273
  produced inside living cells, 

118
00:06:15,275 --> 00:06:17,376
    which are mini factories    
           generating           

119
00:06:17,378 --> 00:06:20,245
   the genetically engineered   
       protein treatments.      

120
00:06:20,247 --> 00:06:23,148
    it's a different approach   
     from traditional drugs,    

121
00:06:23,150 --> 00:06:26,451
     which are manufactured     
    using chemical synthesis.   

122
00:06:26,453 --> 00:06:30,355
   biologics offer hope where   
  other therapies have failed.  

123
00:06:30,357 --> 00:06:32,457
                     ♪♪         

124
00:06:32,459 --> 00:06:35,127
         to mass-produce        
    these biologic medicines,   

125
00:06:35,129 --> 00:06:40,498
  scientists use the molecular  
 machinery inside living cells. 

126
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:43,936
   the process starts with the  
  insertion of genetic material 

127
00:06:43,938 --> 00:06:47,172
      into chinese hamster      
         ovarian cells.         

128
00:06:47,174 --> 00:06:49,908
   they're known as cho cells.  

129
00:06:49,910 --> 00:06:54,246
 they keep them frozen in liquid
  nitrogen until the next step. 

130
00:06:54,248 --> 00:06:58,516
  in the seed lab, a technician 
 thaws the cells in warm water. 

131
00:06:58,518 --> 00:07:01,987
                     ♪♪         

132
00:07:01,989 --> 00:07:04,856
        he transfers them       
        to a glass flask        

133
00:07:04,858 --> 00:07:08,393
   that contains growth media.  

134
00:07:08,395 --> 00:07:11,697
  the growth media is comprised 
    of hundreds of nutrients,   

135
00:07:11,699 --> 00:07:13,765
including vitamins and minerals.

136
00:07:13,767 --> 00:07:16,501
      it's a recipe to help     
       the cells multiply.      

137
00:07:16,503 --> 00:07:20,138
                     ♪♪         

138
00:07:20,140 --> 00:07:23,775
  a worker transfers the flask  
     that contains the cells    

139
00:07:23,777 --> 00:07:27,378
     to the production side     
          of the plant.         

140
00:07:27,380 --> 00:07:29,247
  the team injects the mixture  

141
00:07:29,249 --> 00:07:33,952
    into a 5-gallon-capacity    
           bioreactor.          

142
00:07:33,954 --> 00:07:38,957
  inside, a propeller agitates  
the mixture to stimulate growth.

143
00:07:38,959 --> 00:07:40,525
      over a 3-week period,     

144
00:07:40,527 --> 00:07:44,062
       the number of cells      
    increases exponentially.    

145
00:07:44,064 --> 00:07:45,564
   each new cell is programmed  

146
00:07:45,566 --> 00:07:48,900
      to produce the target     
        biologic protein.       

147
00:07:48,902 --> 00:07:53,571
    a worker sterilizes this    
  21-gallon-capacity bioreactor 

148
00:07:53,573 --> 00:07:56,441
    to prepare it to receive    
        the cell mixture.       

149
00:07:56,443 --> 00:08:00,145
   under precisely controlled   
  conditions in the bioreactor, 

150
00:08:00,147 --> 00:08:03,582
       the cells multiply       
         substantially.         

151
00:08:03,584 --> 00:08:06,885
  over several weeks, the team  
       transfers the cells      

152
00:08:06,887 --> 00:08:10,088
        to progressively        
       larger bioreactors.      

153
00:08:10,090 --> 00:08:13,024
      the cells grow until      
      there are trillions,      

154
00:08:13,026 --> 00:08:16,327
         each producing         
       the target protein.      

155
00:08:16,329 --> 00:08:21,533
   next, a technician measures  
salts and other dry ingredients.

156
00:08:21,535 --> 00:08:25,170
     he's preparing a recipe    
for purifying the protein liquid

157
00:08:25,172 --> 00:08:29,308
    once it's been separated    
         from the cells.        

158
00:08:29,310 --> 00:08:31,977
  he labels the bag and records 
         the information        

159
00:08:31,979 --> 00:08:36,848
     separately as required     
   by government regulations.   

160
00:08:36,850 --> 00:08:41,119
   he adds the ingredients to   
purified water in a mixing tank.

161
00:08:41,121 --> 00:08:43,789
 an automated system keeps tabs 
        on the condition        

162
00:08:43,791 --> 00:08:46,358
  of the purification solution. 

163
00:08:46,360 --> 00:08:50,161
                     ♪♪         

164
00:08:50,163 --> 00:08:52,397
        after separating        
        cellular material       

165
00:08:52,399 --> 00:08:54,032
    from the protein mixture,   

166
00:08:54,034 --> 00:08:57,568
    the team pumps it through   
    steel and glass columns.    

167
00:08:57,570 --> 00:09:01,172
 here, the purification solution
     works with resin beads     

168
00:09:01,174 --> 00:09:03,875
     to separate the protein    
      from the impurities.      

169
00:09:03,877 --> 00:09:07,612
                     ♪♪         

170
00:09:07,614 --> 00:09:10,548
      the purified protein      
    is stored in steel tanks    

171
00:09:10,550 --> 00:09:13,218
    at -4 degrees fahrenheit.   

172
00:09:13,220 --> 00:09:18,023
 it keeps the biologic medicine 
       in a stable state.       

173
00:09:18,025 --> 00:09:20,425
           meanwhile,           
   in the quality control lab,  

174
00:09:20,427 --> 00:09:25,464
  a technician injects a sample 
      into glass capsules.      

175
00:09:25,466 --> 00:09:29,901
  she places the capsules into  
a robotic analytical instrument.

176
00:09:29,903 --> 00:09:33,371
  this sophisticated equipment  
 measures the potency and purity

177
00:09:33,373 --> 00:09:35,507
    of the biologic medicine.   

178
00:09:35,509 --> 00:09:38,443
                     ♪♪         

179
00:09:38,445 --> 00:09:41,412
   once the biologic medicine   
        passes the tests,       

180
00:09:41,414 --> 00:09:44,316
    they prepare glass vials    
         to receive it.         

181
00:09:44,318 --> 00:09:46,584
           that means           
     an intensive cleaning.     

182
00:09:46,586 --> 00:09:48,420
                     ♪♪         

183
00:09:48,422 --> 00:09:52,190
   the automated system loads   
the vials into individual slots,

184
00:09:52,192 --> 00:09:55,160
    and sprayers rinse them.    

185
00:09:55,162 --> 00:09:58,596
   the system then transports   
 the vials through a heat tunnel

186
00:09:58,598 --> 00:10:04,836
 that sterilizes them to remove 
 any potentially harmful toxins.

187
00:10:04,838 --> 00:10:07,406
   moving through an isolated   
          sterile zone,         

188
00:10:07,408 --> 00:10:11,943
        the vials funnel        
      into a fill station.      

189
00:10:11,945 --> 00:10:15,614
   nozzles dispense a specific  
    dose of biologic medicine   

190
00:10:15,616 --> 00:10:19,117
         into the vials.        

191
00:10:19,119 --> 00:10:22,854
      here, plungers insert     
     stoppers in the vials.     

192
00:10:22,856 --> 00:10:24,856
 a camera then takes a picture, 

193
00:10:24,858 --> 00:10:27,325
         and a computer         
      instantly analyzes it     

194
00:10:27,327 --> 00:10:32,364
  to confirm that the stoppers  
 have been correctly installed. 

195
00:10:32,366 --> 00:10:35,500
    the system then caps the    
stoppers to completely seal them

196
00:10:35,502 --> 00:10:37,568
       from contaminants.       

197
00:10:37,570 --> 00:10:40,671
   this machinery hygienically  
         fills and caps         

198
00:10:40,673 --> 00:10:43,775
   over 100 vials per minute.   

199
00:10:43,777 --> 00:10:46,911
        a worker visually       
       inspects each vial.      

200
00:10:46,913 --> 00:10:51,483
he carefully swirls the contents
   as he looks for impurities.  

201
00:10:51,485 --> 00:10:55,153
    if he sees any, the vial    
  of medicine will be rejected. 

202
00:10:55,155 --> 00:10:57,388
                     ♪♪         

203
00:10:57,390 --> 00:11:01,193
 finally, this technician takes 
  a sample and conducts a test  

204
00:11:01,195 --> 00:11:03,328
     to ensure the medicine     
           is sterile.          

205
00:11:05,466 --> 00:11:07,365
     grown in living cells,     

206
00:11:07,367 --> 00:11:10,068
    these biologic medicines    
      are now on their way      

207
00:11:10,070 --> 00:11:14,005
      to potentially making     
 a difference in people's lives.

208
00:11:23,616 --> 00:11:26,718
                     ♪♪         

209
00:11:28,755 --> 00:11:30,822
    narrator: the development   
      of the asphalt paver      

210
00:11:30,824 --> 00:11:33,125
        in the early part       
       of the 20th century      

211
00:11:33,127 --> 00:11:35,694
      changed the way roads     
           were built.          

212
00:11:35,696 --> 00:11:38,596
  the paving machine took over  
        from large crews        

213
00:11:38,598 --> 00:11:42,533
   who paved surfaces manually  
    using picks and shovels.    

214
00:11:42,535 --> 00:11:46,338
   this invention has made it   
  a lot easier to pave the way. 

215
00:11:48,074 --> 00:11:50,074
                     ♪♪         

216
00:11:50,076 --> 00:11:54,646
  the asphalt paver transforms  
  rough roads into smooth ones. 

217
00:11:54,648 --> 00:11:57,949
 this paving machine distributes
       asphalt, levels it,      

218
00:11:57,951 --> 00:12:00,618
        and also provides       
     the initial compaction.    

219
00:12:00,620 --> 00:12:03,155
                     ♪♪         

220
00:12:03,157 --> 00:12:06,858
     making one starts with     
  a computerized plasma cutter. 

221
00:12:06,860 --> 00:12:09,794
    the operator programs it    
   to cut out all the parts of  

222
00:12:09,796 --> 00:12:13,632
       the paver structure      
 from heavy-gauge steel plates. 

223
00:12:13,634 --> 00:12:17,702
 it also configures the cutting 
       to minimize waste.       

224
00:12:17,704 --> 00:12:20,638
  the plasma tooling also cuts  
        and threads holes       

225
00:12:20,640 --> 00:12:23,808
 for bolting the parts together.

226
00:12:23,810 --> 00:12:25,710
  once the parts have been cut, 

227
00:12:25,712 --> 00:12:29,147
     a crane transfers them     
      to a welding fixture.     

228
00:12:29,149 --> 00:12:31,082
                     ♪♪         

229
00:12:31,084 --> 00:12:33,652
   the fixture holds the parts  
       for the paver frame      

230
00:12:33,654 --> 00:12:35,020
       in tight alignment       

231
00:12:35,022 --> 00:12:37,422
      while a welder tacks      
         them together.         

232
00:12:37,424 --> 00:12:40,258
                     ♪♪         

233
00:12:40,260 --> 00:12:43,461
he also tack welds smaller parts
       like engine mounts       

234
00:12:43,463 --> 00:12:45,997
        to the structure.       

235
00:12:45,999 --> 00:12:50,235
  once the tack welds are done, 
 he does full welds throughout, 

236
00:12:50,237 --> 00:12:52,971
  creating strong, thick seams. 

237
00:12:52,973 --> 00:12:55,973
                     ♪♪         

238
00:12:55,975 --> 00:12:59,978
  a team loads more steel into  
   a computerized press break.  

239
00:12:59,980 --> 00:13:01,379
    it clamps the steel plate   

240
00:13:01,381 --> 00:13:03,982
             between            
    a matching punch and die.   

241
00:13:03,984 --> 00:13:06,317
  then, using hydraulic power,  

242
00:13:06,319 --> 00:13:08,987
      the press break makes     
          precise bends         

243
00:13:08,989 --> 00:13:14,192
     to shape the steel into    
 a section of the paver hopper. 

244
00:13:14,194 --> 00:13:17,262
    with the first bend done,   
   one of the workers measures  

245
00:13:17,264 --> 00:13:19,230
 the angle with a digital level 

246
00:13:19,232 --> 00:13:21,566
         to confirm that        
       it's exactly right.      

247
00:13:21,568 --> 00:13:24,168
                     ♪♪         

248
00:13:24,170 --> 00:13:26,938
  the team then moves the steel 
       plate into position      

249
00:13:26,940 --> 00:13:28,539
       for the next bends.      

250
00:13:28,541 --> 00:13:32,243
   they make a total of three   
       in the hopper part.      

251
00:13:32,245 --> 00:13:34,946
    those three bends must be   
        perfectly angled        

252
00:13:34,948 --> 00:13:37,348
      and positioned to fit     
     the rest of the hopper.    

253
00:13:37,350 --> 00:13:41,019
                     ♪♪         

254
00:13:41,021 --> 00:13:44,922
 it's why precision is critical.

255
00:13:44,924 --> 00:13:50,128
  they do a final check of the  
  three bends using a template. 

256
00:13:50,130 --> 00:13:53,497
      next, a welder joins      
 a side panel to the hopper part

257
00:13:53,499 --> 00:13:55,333
      with the three bends.     

258
00:13:55,335 --> 00:13:58,637
      these two parts form      
  the left side of the hopper.  

259
00:13:58,639 --> 00:14:00,805
                     ♪♪         

260
00:14:00,807 --> 00:14:04,175
  after an acid wash, it's into 
     the paint booth to coat    

261
00:14:04,177 --> 00:14:07,612
 the steel with an epoxy primer 
       and urethane paint.      

262
00:14:07,614 --> 00:14:13,985
                     ♪♪         

263
00:14:13,987 --> 00:14:16,121
    the parts then spend time   
           in an oven           

264
00:14:16,123 --> 00:14:19,958
  to accelerate the paint cure. 

265
00:14:19,960 --> 00:14:22,093
        then it's over to       
       the assembly line,       

266
00:14:22,095 --> 00:14:27,065
 where construction of the paver
  tractor is already underway.  

267
00:14:27,067 --> 00:14:30,468
   a worker bolts gear systems  
          to the sides.         

268
00:14:30,470 --> 00:14:33,738
     these gears will drive     
        the paver wheels.       

269
00:14:33,740 --> 00:14:37,041
                     ♪♪         

270
00:14:37,043 --> 00:14:38,643
    with the help of a crane,   

271
00:14:38,645 --> 00:14:43,114
         the team guides        
    the engine into position.   

272
00:14:43,116 --> 00:14:45,850
 the engine's mounting structure
        mates to bushings       

273
00:14:45,852 --> 00:14:47,452
       in four locations.       

274
00:14:47,454 --> 00:14:50,121
                     ♪♪         

275
00:14:50,123 --> 00:14:53,725
 they now assemble the hopper to
the front of the paving machine.

276
00:14:53,727 --> 00:14:56,060
                     ♪♪         

277
00:14:56,062 --> 00:14:59,230
 hinge tubes on the hopper part 
      intermesh with tubes      

278
00:14:59,232 --> 00:15:01,666
          on the center         
       conveyor framework.      

279
00:15:01,668 --> 00:15:04,302
     they'll run a long pin     
    through these hinge tubes   

280
00:15:04,304 --> 00:15:07,539
    to complete the assembly.   

281
00:15:07,541 --> 00:15:09,674
     with everything in good    
         working order,         

282
00:15:09,676 --> 00:15:11,742
     they're ready to build     
           the screed,          

283
00:15:11,744 --> 00:15:14,011
 beginning with the base plate. 

284
00:15:14,013 --> 00:15:16,981
    the screed is a critical    
           apparatus.           

285
00:15:16,983 --> 00:15:19,784
     its system of vibrating    
      extenders both levels     

286
00:15:19,786 --> 00:15:23,888
    and compacts the asphalt    
once it's deposited on the road.

287
00:15:23,890 --> 00:15:25,957
      they're also equipped     
      with heating elements     

288
00:15:25,959 --> 00:15:29,427
  to keep the asphalt workable. 

289
00:15:29,429 --> 00:15:32,163
   they run a battery of tests  
     on all these components    

290
00:15:32,165 --> 00:15:35,567
   to confirm that the screed   
      is fully operational.     

291
00:15:35,569 --> 00:15:38,603
                     ♪♪         

292
00:15:38,605 --> 00:15:43,508
  the screed is now ready to be 
   mated to the paver tractor.  

293
00:15:43,510 --> 00:15:47,245
 they put the tractor in reverse
  and back it up to the screed  

294
00:15:47,247 --> 00:15:50,548
   until brackets on both meet  
      in perfect alignment.     

295
00:15:50,550 --> 00:15:53,484
                     ♪♪         

296
00:15:53,486 --> 00:15:55,987
   once the brackets have been  
        bolted together,        

297
00:15:55,989 --> 00:15:59,791
        the asphalt paver       
       is ready for work.       

298
00:15:59,793 --> 00:16:03,194
   the road ahead will be long  
    and potentially winding,    

299
00:16:03,196 --> 00:16:07,532
 but it should be pretty smooth,
  thanks to this asphalt paver. 

300
00:16:15,775 --> 00:16:19,077
                     ♪♪         

301
00:16:21,348 --> 00:16:23,481
      narrator: espadrilles     
    have been a popular style   

302
00:16:23,483 --> 00:16:26,251
       of casual footwear       
        for decades now,        

303
00:16:26,253 --> 00:16:27,885
         yet most people        
        likely don't know       

304
00:16:27,887 --> 00:16:31,156
       the origin of this       
     comfortable cloth shoe.    

305
00:16:31,158 --> 00:16:35,326
   europeans have been wearing  
  espadrilles since the 1300s.  

306
00:16:35,328 --> 00:16:39,030
  the basque region in northern 
 spain is still famous for them.

307
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:45,670
 espadrilles are fashion forward
    and a step back in time.    

308
00:16:45,672 --> 00:16:48,639
 the people of the basque region
  have been making these cloth  

309
00:16:48,641 --> 00:16:51,476
         and jute shoes         
     for hundreds of years.     

310
00:16:51,478 --> 00:16:57,315
they began reinforcing the soles
 with rubber in the early 1900s.

311
00:16:57,317 --> 00:17:02,219
  jute is a plant fiber that's  
 spun into strong, coarse twine.

312
00:17:02,221 --> 00:17:04,155
     for traditional basque     
          espadrilles,          

313
00:17:04,157 --> 00:17:07,925
   they use twine that's about  
    1/10th of an inch thick.    

314
00:17:07,927 --> 00:17:11,896
     large jute spools feed     
 an automated braiding machine. 

315
00:17:11,898 --> 00:17:14,299
      its five bobbins move     
      in a circular pattern     

316
00:17:14,301 --> 00:17:16,401
      that produces a neat      
         braid measuring        

317
00:17:16,403 --> 00:17:18,536
         roughly 3/4ths         
         of an inch wide        

318
00:17:18,538 --> 00:17:20,738
 by a quarter of an inch thick. 

319
00:17:20,740 --> 00:17:23,307
                     ♪♪         

320
00:17:23,309 --> 00:17:25,610
       right after exiting      
      the braiding machine,     

321
00:17:25,612 --> 00:17:28,178
        the braid enters        
      a calibration machine     

322
00:17:28,180 --> 00:17:32,750
      which applies tension     
 to make the dimensions uniform.

323
00:17:32,752 --> 00:17:37,188
      each espadrille sole      
 is hand-crafted by an artisan. 

324
00:17:37,190 --> 00:17:41,492
  he winds the braid on a form  
 that's more than a century old.

325
00:17:41,494 --> 00:17:44,228
  the positioning of the metal  
        pegs in the holes       

326
00:17:44,230 --> 00:17:47,565
     correspond to the size     
    of the shoe he's making.    

327
00:17:47,567 --> 00:17:49,868
       the closer the pegs      
       are to each other,       

328
00:17:49,870 --> 00:17:52,203
   the smaller the shoe size.   

329
00:17:52,205 --> 00:17:56,774
  after nine rotations for this 
  shoe size, he cuts the braid, 

330
00:17:56,776 --> 00:18:00,544
   then, using a large needle,  
        ties off the end.       

331
00:18:00,546 --> 00:18:03,214
                     ♪♪         

332
00:18:03,216 --> 00:18:06,083
    he places the wound braid   
          into a press          

333
00:18:06,085 --> 00:18:08,252
      which, as we see here     
         in slow motion,        

334
00:18:08,254 --> 00:18:10,855
       compresses it into       
     the shape of the sole.     

335
00:18:10,857 --> 00:18:17,261
                     ♪♪         

336
00:18:17,263 --> 00:18:23,100
  in real time, this step takes 
    just a couple of seconds.   

337
00:18:23,102 --> 00:18:26,971
    then he picks up the sole   
           with a comb          

338
00:18:26,973 --> 00:18:30,041
        and feeds it into       
  an automated sewing machine.  

339
00:18:30,043 --> 00:18:35,345
                     ♪♪         

340
00:18:35,347 --> 00:18:40,317
  two large needles, one above, 
one below, simultaneously stitch

341
00:18:40,319 --> 00:18:43,587
  all the way through the sole  
     with thick jute thread,    

342
00:18:43,589 --> 00:18:45,456
  binding the wound jute braid. 

343
00:18:45,458 --> 00:18:51,930
                     ♪♪         

344
00:18:51,932 --> 00:18:55,899
   this machine sews more than  
  100 pairs of soles per hour.  

345
00:18:55,901 --> 00:18:59,370
                     ♪♪         

346
00:18:59,372 --> 00:19:02,240
    by now, the espadrilles'    
       signature jute sole      

347
00:19:02,242 --> 00:19:03,941
       is formed and sewn,      

348
00:19:03,943 --> 00:19:06,144
but it's not quite finished yet.

349
00:19:06,146 --> 00:19:07,812
 to prevent it from wearing out,

350
00:19:07,814 --> 00:19:10,448
   it needs a protective layer  
           of rubber.           

351
00:19:10,450 --> 00:19:13,284
                     ♪♪         

352
00:19:13,286 --> 00:19:17,322
  the artisan now opens a mold  
 for the corresponding shoe size

353
00:19:17,324 --> 00:19:19,557
            and fills           
    the sole-shaped cavities    

354
00:19:19,559 --> 00:19:23,628
  with a pre-measured quantity  
  of colorless rubber granules. 

355
00:19:23,630 --> 00:19:26,030
                     ♪♪         

356
00:19:26,032 --> 00:19:29,000
         then, he places        
     the jute soles on top.     

357
00:19:29,002 --> 00:19:33,237
                     ♪♪         

358
00:19:33,239 --> 00:19:37,942
he closes the mold and places it
    in a press for 6 minutes.   

359
00:19:37,944 --> 00:19:41,612
    the press heats the mold    
   to 300 degrees fahrenheit,   

360
00:19:41,614 --> 00:19:44,449
  melting the rubber granules.  

361
00:19:44,451 --> 00:19:47,385
    the liquid rubber spreads   
    throughout the cavities,    

362
00:19:47,387 --> 00:19:50,788
   penetrates the jute fibers   
         and vulcanizes,        

363
00:19:50,790 --> 00:19:53,857
  meaning it hardens and cures. 

364
00:19:53,859 --> 00:19:55,793
          this produces         
       a rubber outer sole      

365
00:19:55,795 --> 00:19:57,461
  about 1/6th of an inch thick  

366
00:19:57,463 --> 00:20:00,298
          that protects         
      the jute inner sole.      

367
00:20:00,300 --> 00:20:04,835
the espadrilles' uppers are made
  of 100-percent-cotton canvas. 

368
00:20:04,837 --> 00:20:07,438
       the artisan stacks       
         about 20 pieces        

369
00:20:07,440 --> 00:20:09,440
  and cuts them simultaneously  

370
00:20:09,442 --> 00:20:13,311
    with a razor-like blade.    

371
00:20:13,313 --> 00:20:18,282
  each upper is comprised of a  
  front piece and a back piece. 

372
00:20:18,284 --> 00:20:22,453
   a seamstress sews the upper  
        entirely by hand.       

373
00:20:22,455 --> 00:20:26,290
  she wears a glove that has a  
 copper cup built into the palm,

374
00:20:26,292 --> 00:20:27,458
     which she uses to force    

375
00:20:27,460 --> 00:20:30,961
        the giant needle        
     through the tough jute.    

376
00:20:30,963 --> 00:20:34,265
    after stitching the front   
  and back pieces to the sole,  

377
00:20:34,267 --> 00:20:37,634
   she sews them to each other  
        along the sides.        

378
00:20:37,636 --> 00:20:40,571
                     ♪♪         

379
00:20:40,573 --> 00:20:44,708
  she closes and reinforces the 
toe with three rows of stitches.

380
00:20:44,710 --> 00:20:47,912
                     ♪♪         

381
00:20:47,914 --> 00:20:51,482
   all this with strong, thick  
 thread made of braided cotton. 

382
00:20:51,484 --> 00:20:53,551
                     ♪♪         

383
00:20:53,553 --> 00:20:57,088
this maker of basque espadrilles
     prides itself in using     

384
00:20:57,090 --> 00:21:01,459
     only natural materials,    
  even in the paper packaging.  

385
00:21:01,461 --> 00:21:04,662
  the rubber used for the soles 
      contains no colorants     

386
00:21:04,664 --> 00:21:06,964
 but is infused with citronella,

387
00:21:06,966 --> 00:21:10,834
  a fragrant plant oil believed 
    to help repel mosquitoes.   

388
00:21:10,836 --> 00:21:14,071
                     ♪♪         

